One-Server Web Infrastructure for www.foobar.com
1. User Access

When a user wants to access the website:

The user opens a browser and types www.foobar.com.

The browser sends a DNS query to find the IP address of www.foobar.com.

DNS responds with the server IP: 8.8.8.8.

The browser sends an HTTP/HTTPS request to the server.

2. DNS and Domain Name

Domain Name: foobar.com is a human-readable address for the website.

DNS Record: www is an A record pointing www.foobar.com → 8.8.8.8.

Role: Converts a readable domain into a machine-readable IP address so the browser can reach the server.

3. Server and Components

Server: A physical or virtual machine that handles requests from users.

Inside the server:

Web Server (Nginx):

Receives HTTP/HTTPS requests from users.

Serves static files (images, CSS, JavaScript).

Forwards dynamic requests to the application server.

Application Server:

Runs the website code base.

Processes requests, applies business logic, and generates dynamic content.

Application Files (Code Base):

All scripts and logic that make the website function.

Database (MySQL):

Stores data such as users, posts, products, etc.

Application server queries the database to retrieve or save data.

4. Request Flow

Browser → HTTP request → Nginx (Web Server)

Nginx → Application Server

Application Server → MySQL Database (if needed)

Application Server → Response to Nginx

Nginx → HTTP Response → Browser

Communication: HTTP/HTTPS over TCP/IP.

